In this way, the mathematical expression of the back-calculation method is straightforward, but the estimation of Ii using this method is challenging [17] because of the high dimension of Ii which leads to instability. To estimate the incidence of HIV Ii, several published studies [18, 19] have used either A(t) or I(t) as flexible parametric functions. Rosenberg et al. [20] estimated the infection curve I(s) directly, assuming that I(s) is a member of the general family G={g1(s),⋯,gI(s)}, where gi(s) are integrable real functions. That is,
